Sales and Channel of Sales
         1.  Sale of products directly to automobile and motorcycle manufacturers as an OEM (Original Equipment 
Manufacturer) (or First Tier parts supplier).
         2.  Sale of component parts to automobile and motorcycle part manufacturers (or act as Second Tier parts supplier) 
to further assemble and subsequently supply to automobile and motorcycle manufacturers.
         3.  Sales of products to service & spare parts center as an REM (Replacement Equipment Manufacturer).

Competition within automotive parts industry
         Domestic market
         The Company is a leading automobile control cables manufacturer for both Japanese and non-Japanese automobile
manufacturers which have manufacturing base in Thailand including Toyota, Honda, Isuzu, Mitsubishi, Nissan, ford,
and Mazda.  In 2004, these automobile manufacturers achieved a combined market share of more than 90% of domestic
market.  For motorcycle control cables, the Company's customers are comprised of all Japanese manufacturers including
Honda, Yamaha, Suzuki, and Kawasaki, which collectively controlled more than 95% of total market share in 2004.

         The Company entered into an license and technical assistance agreements with Nippon Cable System Inc. to 
obtain industrial property rights and know-how to manufacture automobile and motorcycle control cables in Thailand.
This allows the Company to produce high-quality products that are widely accepted by automobile and motorcycle 
manufacturers as well as strengthen the Company's competitiveness as a leading control cable manufacturer in Thailand.
As a result, in 2004, the Company's market share for automobile and motorcycle control cables were approximately 
76% and 98%, respectively. (Based on automobile and motorcycle manufacturers' market share)

         The Company also produces window regulators for Honda and Isuzu, whose combined market share were 
approximately 36% in 2004. The Company's window regulators are manufactured based on license and technical 
assistance agreements with Nippon Cable System Inc. and Fuji Kiko Co., Ltd. 

         Export market
         In 2004, exports contribute approximately 3.68% of the Company's total revenue. Majority of these exports 
are component parts which the Company supply OEM parts to companies within Nippon Cable System Group in 
other countries including Malaysia, Vietnam, Japan, China, India, and Indonesia. Competitions in the automotive 
parts business is likely to intensify, particularly within South  East Asian countries, as automobile manufacturers are 
implementing a more stringent purchasing policy which put high emphasis on cost reduction. This strategy is likely 
to benefit part manufacturers in countries such as China, whose labor cost is relatively inexpensive comparing to 
Thailand. Nonetheless, given TSC's outstanding product quality, extensive track records, long-term relationship with 
automobile manufacturers, and license and technical assistance agreements with Nippon Cable System Inc. and Fuji 
Kiko Co., Ltd., the Company is confident that we still have advantage over competitors.

Raw Material purchasing 
         The Company purchases raw materials and component parts from both domestic and international suppliers.  
In 2004, the Company purchases raw materials in the amount equivalent to  THB 1,146.24 million,  or approximately
88.10% of total purchases. Of this amount, approximately 69% is domestic purchases while the other 31% is 
international purchases.  In 2004, there were only 2 suppliers who individually account for more than 10% of the
Company's total purchases - Nippon Cable System Inc. (account for 23.24% of the Company's total purchases) 
and Jideco (Thailand) Co., Ltd. (account for 14.24% of the Company's total purchases). Details of raw materials 
purchased from each supplier are as followed;
         1.  Nippon Cable System Inc.: Bolt Joint, Boot Assembly, Bracket Assembly, Cap Assembly, Carrier Plate, 
Casing Cap, steel, and plastic polymer for manufacturing of control cables and window regulators.
         2.   Jideco (Thailand) Co., Ltd.: Motor for window regulators.
         Note : There is no obligation for the Company to purchase raw materials from Nippon Cable System Inc., who 
is a Company's major shareholder.

         For control cables, in 2004, domestic supplies accounted for approximately 67% of total raw material purchases 
for automobile and motorcycle control cables. Most of these raw materials (approximately 60%) are rubber, plastic 
polymer, and steel wire  For window regulators, in 2004, domestic supplies account for approximately 75% of total 
raw material purchases. Majorities of these are steel and electric motor, which the Company sourced.
  
Environmental Impacts
         The Company places high emphasis on environmental management as reflected in the hiring of N-Technology 
Consultant, which is an expert on hazard and waste management, to manage the Company's waste from manufacturing
process.   During 2002 - 2004, the Company had spent approximately THB 0.10, 0.06, and 0.21 million for waste 
management.  The Company follows  Department of Industry Works (DIW) requirements by reporting to DIW monthly.
The Company's handling of waste management is a major factor that TUV awarded ISO 14001 to the Company in 2000. 

Summary of Material Contracts
         1)  License and Technical Assistance Agreement
             The Company entered into an agreement with Nippon Cable System Inc. to obtain the Industrial Property 
Rights and/or Know-how and technical assistance to manufacture control cable for automobile and motorcycle and 
their parts.  Nippon Cable System Inc. also grants to the Company the right to use Trademarks "TSK" and "HI-LEX" 
with respect to the licensed products.  This agreement is valid and in force for a period of 7 years from September 15,
1998 and will be extended for a period of one year after the expiration subject to the conditions set forth in the 
agreement.  In return, the Company has to pay Nippon Cable System Inc. running royalties in an amount equal to 
2% of the net sales amount during the term of this agreement.  Net Selling Price means the price at which the 
Company sells licensed products to a nonaffiliated third party after deducting (a) cost of packaging, insurance, 
freight and warehouse, business discount and sales tax to be paid by the Company and (b) the price of those parts 
purchased from Nippon Cable System Inc. 

             The Company has already received the Letter of Intent from Nippon Cable System Inc. stating its intention to 
extend the validity of this agreement for another 5 years from September 15, 2006 which is the current expiration date
of this agreement. 

         2)  License and Technical Assistance Agreement
             The Company entered into this agreement with Nippon Cable System Inc. to obtain the Industrial Property
Rights and/or Know-how and technical assistance to manufacture cable-type window regulator and their parts.  
Nippon Cable System Inc. also grants to the Company the right to use Trademarks "TSK" and "HI-LEX" with 
respect to the licensed products.  This agreement is valid and in force for a period of 10 years from March 4, 1997
and will be extended for a period of one year after the expiration subject to the conditions set forth in the agreement.
In return, the Company has to pay Nippon Cable System Inc. running royalties in an amount equal to 2% of the 
net sales amount during the term of this agreement.  Net Selling Price means the price at which the Company sells
licensed products to a nonaffiliated third party after deducting (a) cost of packaging, insurance, freight and 
warehouse, business discount and sales tax to be paid by the Company and (b) the price of those parts purchased 
from Nippon Cable System Inc. 

             The Company has already received the Letter of Intent from Nippon Cable System Inc. stating its intention
to extend the validity of this agreement for another 5 years from March 4, 2008 which is the current expiration date
of this agreement. 

         3)  Technical License Agreement
              The Company entered into this agreement with Fuji Kiko Company Limited to obtain the Know-how and 
technical assistance to manufacture the automotive arm & sector window regulator to be used for GMT-355/ISUZU I-190
Model.  This agreement is valid and in force for a period of 10 years from January 12, 2000.  In return, the Company
has to pay Fuji Kiko Company Limited an initial payment of USD 30,000, a running royalty of 2% of the Net Sales 
Value of the licensed product for the first 2 years after start of production and a running royalty of 3% for the 
remaining term of this agreement.  Net Sales Value means the sales value of the licensed product sold by the Company
less sales tax, packaging, transportation, and also less the C.I.F. value of any components, parts or materials purchased 
by the Company from Fuji Kiko Company Limited or manufactured by Fuji Kiko Company Limited.

             Upon the expiration date of this agreement, if the Company still needs license and technical assistance for the 
manufacture of x-arm type window regulator for GMT-355/ISUZU I-190 Model or other models, the Company has 
to entered into a new agreement with Fuji Kiko Company Limited or other companies who own such know-how.  
Decisions on this will be based on the customer's requirement in the future.

         4)  Auto Parts Purchase and Sale Agreement entered into with Isuzu Motors (Thailand) Company Limited, Honda
Automobile (Thailand) Company Limited, Toyota Motor Thailand Company Limited and Thai Honda Manufacturing 
Company Limited 
             These agreements are Purchase and Sale Agreements the Company entered into with the above-mentioned 
automobile and motorcycle makers for selling of auto parts for automobile and motorcycle.  All these agreements have 
a validity of 1 year and will be automatically extended for a period(s) of 1 year at a time unless either party indicates 
their clear intention to terminate the agreement.  In addition, these agreements also have clauses of product warranty 
and third party warranty which indicates the Company's responsibilities in case of third party injury or property 
damages as a result of product defect.

             Note: These agreements describe only general terms and conditions mutually agreed by both parties for the 
selling and purchasing of products.  Prior to auto parts purchase, each automobile and motorcycle maker will announce
its production plan and specifications of the auto parts for each automobile and motorcycle model.  The Company has 
to make a design and produce a prototype of its product and submits to the automobile and/or motorcycle maker for
consideration.  If the Company is chosen to be the supplier for such auto parts, the automobile and/or motorcycle 
maker will submit the periodic purchase order to the Company based on its production plan.

Feasibility Study                       - None -

Technical and Management Assistance 
         The Company has received license and technical assistance from Nippon Cable System Inc. for manufacturing 
of automobile control cables, motorcycle control cables and cable-type window regulators.  The Company has also 
received license and technical assistance from a Japanese firm called Fuji Kiko Company Limited for the manufacturing
of x-arm type window regulators

Future Projects
         1.   Production Capacity Expansion and Factory Relocation Project
              The Company plans to invest in the expansion of its production capacity.  Currently, the Company is to 
build a 20,000 square meter manufacturing facility on 50-Rai land plot located in the Amatanakorn Industrial Estate 
in Chonburi Province.  The total value of the investment plan for building new facility is about THB 395 million in 
which THB 140 million will be allocated to land acquisition, THB 160 million for building construction, THB 75 
million for Machinery and Equipment (additional equipment) and another THB 20 million will cover other expenses
of the project.

             When completed, the new facility will have total production capacity of 30 million units per year (including 
both control cables and  window regulators line).  The Company plans to relocate all of its control cable (automobile
and motorcycle) and window regulators production lines from the existing facility to the new location.  The Company
plans to use the existing facility as a distribution center & office location and may consider other options as deem 
appropriate.  Also, the Company plans to apply for the BOI privilege from the Office of the Board of Investment to
obtain tax and duty benefits.  In principle, the company is eligible to receive 7-year income tax exemption under the 
Relocation Promotional Campaign as it plans to relocate its operations from Investment Promotion Zone 1 to 
Investment Promotion Zone 2.  The Company will be entitled to this privilege from the first day it operates in the 
new factory.

             The Company has entered into a Land Sales/Purchase Agreement with Amatanakorn Industrial Estate and 
placed sum deposits of THB 28 million with Amatanakorn Industrial Estate.  It is expected that the factory construction
will commence by the third quarter of 2005 and will be completed in the fourth quarter of 2006.  Funding for the 
project will be from IPO.

         2.  Other Investment Projects
             The Company also plans to purchase advanced product quality testing equipment e.g. Vibration Durability 
Testing Machine and Heat/Cold Durability Testing Machine, which are important to test performance of control 
cables.  Having its own quality testing equipment will help the Company to save time while reducing expenses as 
well as providing better service its clients as the Company does not have to send demo products to Japan for 
performance testing.  This testing equipment is expected to cost approximately THB  5 million.  The Company is
currently under negotiation for the purchase.  Funding for the project will be from internal cash flow.

