Measures or Procedure for the Approval of Related Transactions
         In the event that the Company considers to enter into a transaction with other persons that may have conflict of 
interest, the Audit Committee will review and provide opinions on rationale for the transaction and appropriateness of 
commercial terms.  This will include a review to ensure that the conditions set out are consistent to normal industry 
practice and comparison will be made to compare with commercial terms of other transactions done with non-related
parties or market prices.  If the Audit Committee does not have adequate expertise to opine on the related transaction,
the Company will appoint independent expert or the auditor of the Company to review and give comments on such 
transaction.  Such comments will be used for decision-making by the Board of Directors or the Audit Committee or 
the shareholders (as the case maybe).  Directors with conflicts of interests will abstain from voting on such transaction.
All related transactions will be disclosed in the notes to the financial statements audited or reviewed by the auditor of the 
Company.

         In addition, after the Company became a listed company in the Stock Exchange of Thailand, the Company must 
strictly comply with the rules, conditions, and guidelines stipulated by the Stock Exchange of Thailand concerning the 
Connected Transaction and the Acquisition and Disposition of Assets.

Policy or Tendency of Related Transactions in the future
         In the future, the Company may enter into related transactions as appropriate.   In doing so, the Company 
will ensure compliance with Securities and Stock Exchange laws and regulations, notifications, orders or requirement 
of the Stock Exchange of Thailand and compliance with the accounting standards concerning disclosure of person's 
information or related transaction stipulated by the Institute of Certified Accountants and Auditors of Thailand.

         For normal business transactions i.e. parts procurement, purchasing of raw materials and component parts, 
and selling of products which will occur as part of the Company's business in the future, the Company has set out 
the criteria and guidelines as follows:
         -   Being the price and conditions which the Company receives from or offers to non-related  persons
         -   Being the price and conditions which a connected person offers to non-related persons
         -   Being the price and conditions which the Company can prove to be the price and conditions that another 
operator of  similar business offers to non-related persons
         -   Being the general trading conditions and the commercial can be calculated with reference to asset's 
value or other measurable means.

         Nevertheless, if the Company decides to enter into related transactions which are not normal business 
transactions as described above, the Audit Committee and/or experts i.e. independent auditor or independent 
appraiser will be appointed to review and opine on such transactions, which will be presented to the Board of 
Directors or shareholders in order to ensure that such transactions are for the maximum benefit of all shareholders.

Contingencies and Commitments
         1.  As of March 31, 2005, the Company has requested a local financial institution to issue a letter of guarantee 
in the amount of THB 1.25 million to Metropolitan Electricity Authority. This letter entitles MEA as the beneficiary 
and shares the same collateral with other long-term loan facility.

         2.  The Board of Directors meeting no. 1/2547, which was held on march 2, 2004, passed a resolution to 
purchase a plot of land from one company with the land value of approximately THB 38 million and the Company 
has subsequently placed THB 10.26 million as a deposit for such land purchase.  The Board of Directors No. 2/2548,
which was held on April 27, 2005, passed another resolution to purchase more land to accommodate the Company's 
new investment plan.  As a result of the second Board of Directors resolution, the Company is now required to invest 
approximately THB 140 million for the land.  The Company has placed additional deposit of THB 17.74 million for 
this land purchase.

Risk Factors
         1.  Risk from Dependence on Major Shareholders
             1.1  Dependence on Production Technology from Nippon Cable System Inc. in Manufacturing of Control 
Cable and Cable-type Window Regulator
                  The Company manufactures its products based on licenses received from Nippon Cable System Inc. 
pertaining to 2 License and Technical Assistance Agreements.  In 2004, the sales revenue generated from products 
manufactured under these licenses is accounted for 91.50% of total sales revenue.  Since such agreements will expire 
in 2006 and 2008, respectively, the Company is subject  to risk if it is unable to extend both agreements beyond the 
expiration dates.
 
                  However, the Company expects that the chance of failing to extend the agreements with Nippon Cable 
System Inc. is minimal because Nippon Cable System Inc. is a major shareholder of the Company who will be holding 
26.94% of paid-up capital after IPO.  In addition, Nippon Cable System Inc. has already given written intention that it 
will extend the agreements' terms for another 5 years after each agreement's expiration date. The Company is assured 
that Nippon Cable System Inc., having invested in the Company for more  than 24 years, will continue to be a committed
shareholder who will support the Company's future growth.  Hence, risk from not obtaining an extension of license 
and technical assistance agreement from this major shareholder is relatively remote.

             1.2   Dependence on Purchase of Raw Materials and Component Parts from Nippon Cable System Inc.
                   During 2002 - 2004 the Company ordered raw materials and component parts from Nippon Cable System Inc.,
a major shareholder, for the total amount of THB 159.72 million, THB 213.10 million, and THB 266.42 million or 
27.54%, 24.69%, and 23.24% of total raw materials and component parts purchases, respectively.  The Company 
needed to buy raw materials and component parts from Nippon Cable System Inc. because these raw materials or 
component parts are not manufactured in Thailand or it is not economical for  the Company to produce these materials 
or component parts by itself or the Company is unable to buy such raw materials from other supplier in Thailand.  As 
such, there are risks associated with purchasing raw materials and component parts from the major shareholder which 
may affect the business operations, financial status, and operating performance of the Company in the future.

                 However, during recent years, the Company has never encountered difficulties in purchasing raw materials 
and component parts from Nippon Cable System Inc. Thus, the Company believes that risk from losing a major supplier
of raw materials and component parts who is also the Company's major shareholder, is comparatively minimal.  In 
addition, with double-sourcing policy, the Company believes that it can immediately switch to other suppliers in Japan 
if there is any difficulty purchasing from Nippon Cable System Inc. (but the Company may have to bear possible higher 
cost).  Furthermore, the Company has no contractual obligation to purchase raw materials and component parts from 
Nippon Cable  System Inc.

             1.3   Dependence on Trademarks and Reputation of Nippon Cable System Inc.
                 Reputation and trademarks ("TSK" and "HI-LEX") of Nippon Cable System Inc. are widely accepted by 
automobile and motorcycle manufacturers worldwide.  These factor leads to the Company's ability to acquire new 
customers and retain existing customer base, especially markets in the countries without Nippon Cable System Inc.'s 
presence.  

                 As such, without assistance from Nippon Cable System Inc. in terms of reputation and trademarks, the 
Company may encounter problems in customer retention or customer acquisition.  

                 However, the Company believes that the well-established relationship between the Company and Nippon 
Cable System Inc. during the past 24 years as well as significant shareholding proportion of Nippon Cable System 
Inc. in the Company will motivate Nippon  Cable system Inc. to further strengthen the Company.  It is, thus, unlikely 
that Nippon Cable System Inc. will exit from being an alliance of the Company.

         2.   Risk from International Competition
              2.1  The Use of Other Manufacturing Bases in South East Asia by Nippon Cable System Inc. to Manufacture 
Products and Export to Thailand
                    Based on the ASEAN Free Trade Area (AFTA), 10 ASEAN members agreed to reduce tariff levied on 
a wide range of products traded within the region to 0% within 2015. This may increase the possibility that Nippon 
Cable System Inc. will consider setting up new manufacturing base and/or using current manufacturing bases in 
Indonesia, Malaysia, and Vietnam to produce automobile and motorcycle control cables and sell directly to the 
automobile and motorcycle manufacturers in Thailand.  This may affect the business operations, financial status, 
and operating performance of the Company in the future. 
 
                  However, the Company believes that the risk of competition from companies within Nippon Cable System 
Inc. Group is minimal  as the Company has the competitive production cost and advantages over other manufacturing 
bases, particularly in terms of delivery costs, better after-sales service, ability to respond to customers' needs, and 
the Company's long-term relationship with automobile and motorcycle manufacturers in Thailand.

                 More importantly, according to the conditions set forth in the License and Technical Assistance 
Agreement that each companies in Nippon Cable System Inc. Group agreed with Nippon Cable System Inc., each 
company needs to seek permission from Nippon Cable System Inc. prior to exporting its products outside its own 
country.  This condition is designed to prevent competition among companies within the group. With Nippon Cable 
System Inc.'s involvement in the Company for more than 24 years, the Company believes that the risk from 
international competition by other companies within Nippon Cable System Inc. in South East Asia is minimal.

            2.2  Competition from International Competitors (Non-member of Nippon Cable System Inc. Group of 
Companies)  
                 With the government policy aiming to establish a free trade area with other countries with reducing tariff 
scheme to stimulate international trade, there is high possibility that there will be more international manufacturers of 
automobile and motorcycle control cable and window regulator who will export their products into Thailand.  This 
increasing competition may come from countries within AFTA or outside AFTA, especially from China.  This may 
affect business operations, financial status, and operating performance of the Company in the future.

                  Nevertheless, the Company believes that it will be able to keep up with the competition since the Company
has a competitive production cost that is considered lower or comparable to the production cost in other countries 
including China for products with comparable quality.  In addition, since automobile and motorcycle manufacturers
have manufacturing bases in Thailand, the Company has advantages over other international competitors in terms 
of delivery cost and customer service.  More importantly, due to the policy of automobile and motorcycle 
manufacturers to maintain minimal level of inventory, imports from abroad which require a higher level of inventory 
will not be harmonious with such policy. 

                  Furthermore, as the Company's has established long-term business relationship with automobile and 
motorcycle manufacturers  in Thailand for more than 26 years, the Company's believes that the risk from 
competition from international competitors is low.

         3.   Risk from Fluctuations in Raw Material Prices
               Prices of the Company's raw materials fluctuate according to the demand and supply of steel, plastic and 
rubber products in  the world market, which is beyond the Company's control and may affect business operations, 
financial status, and operating performance of the Company in the future.

              However, the Company believes that it can adjust its prices to reflect significant increases in raw material 
prices.  For instance, according to Parts Purchase and Sale Agreements the Company entered into with its customers,
the Company and the customers agreed that the selling price can be adjusted from time to time i.e. every 6 months
or if material price fluctuates more than 3%.  

         4.  Risk from Fluctuations in Foreign Exchange Rates
              In 2004, the Company imported raw materials in the amount equal to approximately 31% of total purchase
of raw materials and component parts.  Total value of materials purchased in foreign exchange currency for the 
year 2004 equals to THB 351.20 million.  The Company is, therefore, subject to risk from fluctuating foreign 
exchange rates whenever foreign  currency strengthens against THB.  

            However, the Company has already obtained a foreign exchange forward facility from a financial institution 
in the amount  equivalent to THB 130 million, which the Company can always utilize whenever material fluctuation 
is expected. 
  
         5.   Risk from Dependence on Major Customers
              Currently, the Company has 4 major customers which comprise of 3 major automobile manufacturers and 
1 major motorcycle manufacturer.  Revenue generated from these 4 customers accounted for 71% and 68% of the 
Company's total revenue in 2003 and 2004, respectively.  Therefore, the Company may be subject to revenue risk
when any one of the 4 customers reduces production quantity or stops procuring from the Company.  

             However, since the Company has been in the business for over 26 years, it has gained  reputation through 
high product quality and efficient production technology, resulting in competitive cost of production.  Having Nippon 
Cable System Inc., Japan's leading control cable manufacturer, as a major shareholder and being a member of 
Summit Auto Group,  one of Thailand's premier automobile and motorcycle parts supplier,   the Company believes
that it is unlikely for these 4 automobile and motorcycle manufacturers to switch to Company's competitors.  
Moreover, the Company  also has a risk diversification policy by putting more emphasis on exporting its products 
to other countries in order to minimize risk from depending on major customers.

         6.  Risk from Dependence on Principal Management who are also Major Shareholders of the Company
              The Company was established by 2 co-founders, namely Mr. Sunsurn Jurangkool and Mr. Choothong 
Patanatmarueng, who are highly experienced in the automotive industry and have well-established relationships 
with automobile and motorcycle manufacturers both in and outside Thailand for more than 26 years.  Without 
the two executives, the Company may experience difficulties retaining or acquiring new customers.  However, 
since the total number of shares held by Jurangkool Family and Patanatmarueng Family will still account for 
43.42% of total paid-up capital of the Company after IPO, both executives are likely to be motivated to manage 
the Company in the future.  

         7.  Risk from having major shareholders who collectively hold more than 50% of the Company's total 
shares, complete management  control, and potential conflict of interest among major shareholders, the Company,
and other shareholders  
             Currently, there are 3 groups of major shareholders, namely Jurangkool Family, Patanatmarueng Family
and Nippon Cable System Inc. who will collectively hold 70.36% of total paid-up capital of the Company after 
IPO.  This shareholding proportion gives the major shareholders control over the resolution of shareholders' 
meeting.   As a result, other shareholders may not be able to objectively monitor and oppose to what major 
shareholders proposed to the shareholders' meeting.  In some cases, interest of major shareholders may conflict 
with interests of the Company and of other shareholders.

             In addition, major shareholders have management control over the Company by appointing 7 out of 10 
directors and all of the Executive Committee.  There is risk associated with the major shareholders completely 
controlling the Company's operations, and exercising their power by involving in transactions that may conflict 
with interests of the Company and/or minor shareholders.  

             However, the Company believes that 3 outside independent directors will be in a position to review 
management performance  and perform due care for interests of minor shareholders.  The Company's regulations
also provide that directors with conflicts of interests to abstain from voting on transactions that may conflict with
the interests of the Company and/or minor shareholders.

             The Company also employs independent experts, i.e. Deloitte Touche Tohmatsu Jaiyos Company Limited, 
to regularly review the operations and evaluate the Company's internal control system in order to assist the Company
in developing the appropriate internal control system in accordance with Good Corporate Governance principles, 
which will result in transparent working procedures that can be monitored.  It is, therefore, unlikely that such risk
will take place.

         8.  Risk Associated with Failures to Control Product Quality as Required by the Customers
             Historically, the Company has not been fined or received any notices for termination of the purchase 
and sale agreement as a  result of failure to meet customer's requirements.  Aware of damaging effect of such 
risk, the Company strictly implements product quality control process by setting goals in production, production
costs, quality, logistic and safety.  Consequently, the Company closely monitors the actual performance and 
continuously studies the problems that occur.  From over 26 years of the Company's experience, it believes 
that it can create customer confidence through continuously and consistently provide high quality products and 
services.  The Company has also received ISO 9002:1994 QS 9000 ISO 14001 and ISO/TS 16949 Certificates 
for meeting international standards of production quality, which further reduce risk associated with failure to 
meet customer's quality requirements.

         9.  Risk Associated with Warranty Claim
              If the automobile and motorcycle manufacturers request the Company to pay compensation for damages 
(warranty claim) higher than or equal to the Company's sales to those manufacturers, provided that the Supreme 
Court renders final judgment ordering the Company to make such payments, it may affect the business operations, 
financial status, and operating performance of the Company in the future.

             However, in 2004 the Company received warranty claims for damages by customers in the amount of THB 
560,699, which accounts for only 0.03% of the Company's total sales in 2004.  This 0.03% warrantee claim was 
considered insignificant and common in the course of business and does not affect customers' decision to place 
order. So far this warrantee claim has not created any material adverse impacts to the normal operations of the 
Company.  

         10.  Risk from Dependence on Automobile and Motorcycle Industry
              If the automobile and motorcycle industry is in recession or in stagnation, the Company's business 
operations, financial status, and operating performance in the future may be affected since the Company is in the 
automobile and motorcycle parts industry.

             However, since the government clearly announced a policy to promote Thailand as the center of Asia's 
automotive industry (Detroit of Asia) and  the Ministry of Industry's Thailand Automotive Master Plan - 
which aims to boost domestic production of automobiles and motorcycles from 742,000 units and 2,424,678 
units in 2003 to 1,800,000 units and 3,000,000 units in 2010 and to increase the value of automobile and 
motorcycle parts exports from THB 114,352 million in 2003 to THB 400,000 million in 2010 (Source: 
Automotive Institute) the chance that the automobile and motorcycle industry will go into recession or 
stagnant period in the near future is minimal.  As such, risk associated with dependence of the Company's 
operations on automobile and motorcycle industry is minimized.

         11.  Risk from Competition in Automobile and Motorcycle Parts Industry
             The automotive parts manufacturing industry is a highly competitive industry with a large number of 
manufacturers - both in and outside Thailand.  If the Company loses market share to competitors, it may affect 
business operations, financial status, and operating performance of the Company in the future. Considering the 
fact that automobile and motorcycle manufacturers require high quality parts that has been produced efficiently and 
that  automobile and motorcycle companies will select part manufacturers before the actual production period, which 
the selected ones will continuously receive purchase orders from the automobile and motorcycle manufacturers 
throughout the model life cycle of each automobile and motorcycle model (the average model life cycle of an 
automobile model is 4-8 years while the average model life cycle of a motorcycle model is 2-3 years), the 
Company believes that automobile and motorcycle manufacturers will primarily place orders with producers 
who can provide high quality products with proven long-term track record. TSC, as one of the largest producer 
of automobile and motorcycle control cables and window regulators for an extended period of time with widely 
accepted high quality product lines, is confident that the Company has advantage over its competitors in producing
control cables and window regulators for assembling of automobile and motorcycles in Thailand.

Lawsuit                                 - None -

No. of Employees                 As of March 31, 2005 the Company has 563 employees  

Company Background
         The Company was found on June 12, 1978 with the initial registered capital of THB 4 million.  Its original 
business objective was to produce motorcycle control cables for motorcycle manufacturers in Thailand.  The 
Company's initial production capacity was 250,000 units per year.  In 1981, the Company increased its registered
capital to THB 10 million to expand production capacity to support rapid growth of the automotive industry and
the Thai economy.  In the same year, Nippon Cable System Inc., a leading Japanese manufacturer of automobile
and motorcycle control cables, became a joint venture partner, holding 35% of registered capital.  The Company 
also received license and technical assistance from Nippon Cable System Inc. for the manufacturing of control 
cables.

         In 1982, the Company officially started producing automobile control cable with Mitsubishi as the initial 
customer and then  expanded to other automobile manufacturers.  The Company officially began production of 
window regulator in 1997 with the initial production capacity of 150,000 sets per year.  In the same year, the 
Company was certified ISO 9002:1994.

         In 1998, the Company increased its registered capital to THB 200 million and jointly invested in Hi-Lex 
Vietnam Company Limited with Nippon Cable System Inc. with the purpose to manufacture motorcycle control 
cables in Vietnam.  In addition, the Company has entered into Technical License Agreement with Fuji Kiko 
Company Limited for the manufacturing of x-arm type window regulator.  The Company was subsequently certified 
QS 9000 in 1999, ISO 14001 in 2001 and ISO/TS 16949 in 2005.

         In February 2005, the extraordinary shareholders meeting passed a resolution transforming the Company 
into a Public Company Limited, increasing the registered capital from THB 200 million to THB 268.50 million 
by issuing new 68.50 million shares and changing its par value from THB 100 per share to THB 1 per share.  
Of these new shares, 1.50 million shares will be for right offering and 58.30 million shares will be for the initial 
public offering.  In March 2005, the Company was transformed into Public Company Limited and 1.50 million 
right offering shares were placed at THB 1 per share on April 1, 2005.

